# Playwright Test Standards

## Test Structure

- Use descriptive test names that clearly state what is being tested
- Group related tests in the same file
- Import `test` and `expect` from `@playwright/test`

// ✅ GOOD
test("user can login with valid credentials", async ({ page }) => {
  // test implementation
});

// ❌ BAD
test("login", async ({ page }) => {
  // test implementation
});


## Locator Strategies
Prefer semantic locators in this order:
getByRole() - Most accessible and stable
getByPlaceholder() - For form inputs
getByText() - For text content
getByTestId() - For test-specific attributes
CSS selectors - When semantic locators aren't available
XPath - Only as last resort (avoid if possible)

'''
// ✅ GOOD
await page.getByRole("button", { name: "Login" }).click();
await page.getByPlaceholder("Username").fill("Admin");

// ❌ BAD
await page.locator('//button[text()="Login"]').click(); // XPath
await page.locator("#username").fill("Admin"); // Fragile ID selector
'''

## Page Navigation
Use page.goto() with full URLs for external sites
Consider using baseURL in config for internal applications
Wait for navigation to complete before interacting with elements

'''
// ✅ GOOD
await page.goto("https://opensource-demo.orangehrmlive.com/");
await expect(page).toHaveURL(/demo.orangehrmlive/);

// ❌ BAD
await page.goto("https://opensource-demo.orangehrmlive.com/");
await page.locator("button").click(); // No wait for page load
'''

## Test Cleanup
Avoid manual page.close() calls - Playwright handles this automatically
Use fixtures for setup/teardown when needed
Let Playwright manage browser lifecycle

## Best Practices
Use async/await consistently
Add meaningful wait strategies when needed (Playwright auto-waits, but explicit waits help for complex scenarios)
Keep tests focused - one scenario per test
Use descriptive variable names for locators when reused
Follow the existing project structure and naming conventions


